node.text: Photo by @celestesloman // Sponsored by @century21 // National Geographic Explorer Rae Wynn-Grant, Ph.D., a large carnivore ecologist, spends quality time in her backyard with her partner, Dave, and their two young daughters. During the pandemic Rae moved with her family from New York to Santa Barbara, California, to be closer to her research and have more space for her growing family. Their backyard features orange and avocado trees and provides a perfect place for her children to play and explore. // Home can be our sanctuary and has long been a symbol of security and safety. We've all spent more time in our homes this past year—maybe more than we had ever imagined. How has your relationship evolved with your own home as a result? Whether you live in a studio apartment in an urban high-rise, a suburban sanctuary with a fenced backyard, or someplace in between, we want to see your stories of home. Upload your images to your feed, tag @natgeoyourshot, and use #StoriesofHomeChallenge. I'll be curating submissions and featuring my favorites on the Your Shot account! // By posting with this hashtag, you agree to Nat Geo’s Terms of Use at natgeo.com/future-of-home, and that your photo does not infringe any third party’s rights.

node.text: Photo by Sam Austin @samsnaps77 / I got to experience the Fagradalsfjall volcano up close and it was amazing! Watching the lava change shape every few minutes was one of the coolest things I’ve witnessed. I haven’t had the time to go through all the images I captured, but this image grabbed my eye during a quick look through.

node.text:
Photo by @doug_gimesy / What can you see from there? / As the sun starts to rise, a leopard sits on a tree branch overlooking the Okavango Delta grassland in Botswana. The leopard is one of the five existing species in the genus of Panthera (a member of the cat family, Felidae), the others being the lion, jaguar, tiger, and snow leopard. 
Occurring widely in Africa, the Caucasus, and Asia, the leopard has the largest distribution of all wild cats. Sadly (and not surprisingly), populations are fragmented and declining as a result of habitat fragmentation and conversion of forest to agriculturally used land. This of course leads to a declining natural prey base, human–wildlife conflict with livestock herders, and high leopard mortality rates. Currently, the leopard is listed as vulnerable on the IUCN Red List. #YourShotPhotographer #leopard #cat #botswana

node.text:
Photo by @irina_sigl_photography / The half-timbered houses of the historic old town of Pottenstein in Franconian Switzerland, Germany, nestle picturesquely against the bizarre rocks of the karst mountains, which formed millions of years ago. I particularly liked the cloud formation, which looked as if it was trying to imitate the shape of the rocks.
Nikon D600, 70mm, f/5.6, 1/1200s, ISO 200. #YourShotPhotographer

node.text: Photos by @sarmistha_bera / Baranti is a small tribal village in Purulia, a district in the state of West Bengal. It is situated beside Baranti Lake with hills surrounding it. This calm and quiet place is known for its natural beauty. The lake changes color from time to time during sunset. It’s a real treat to sit and watch the shades of blue, yellow, and red reflected on the water. This is a series of shots taken on the same day at different times. #YourShotPhotographer #colors #sunset #india

node.text:
Photo by @ivan_lesica / While walking through the forest in Accord, New York, I noticed a caterpillar on a backlit leaf. When I started taking photos, the caterpillar was near the center of the leaf. But this beautiful creature must have sensed my presence and started walking around. I captured the moment when the caterpillar peeked its head over the edge. 
SONY HX400V, f/3.2, 5.52mm, ISO 80, 1/800s. #YourShotPhotographer #Caterpillar #nature #macro #sunlight
